ommunities in America. Explosives work was dangerous, but the du Ponts provided a host of benefits to their workers. As a result, the Irish remained loyal to their employers, convinced by their everyday experiences that their interests and the du Ponts' were one and the same. Employing a wide array of sources, Mulrooney turns away from the worksite and toward the domestic sphere, revealing that powder mill families asserted their distinctive ethno-religious heritage at the same time as they embraced what U.S. capitalism had to offer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIrish AmericanszBrandywine Creek Valley (Pa. and Del.)xEthnic identity. 0aIrish AmericanszBrandywine Creek Valley (Pa. and Del.)xHistoryy19th century. 0aWorking classzBrandywine Creek Valley (Pa. and Del.)xHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aHagley powder mill, race and ethnic studies, cultural studies, labor studies, labor history, American studies, nineteenth-century studies, American history, nineteenth-century America, Delaware history, regional studies, Irish studies, Irish diaspora studies, Irish immigrants, Irish American, Irish community, the du Pont Irish, Irish powder workers, gunpowder, history of gunpowder, black powder, black powder industry, immigrant workers, worker's equity, domestic life, domesticity, worker's benefits, worker equality, unions.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2022 Englishz978311099296008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2022z9783110992939oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University